/*minwageDP.gau : This is a program using dynamic programming to solve the decision rules
on a model with durables and non-durables consumption.  It then runs a simulation 
with those rules.
Writes to disk decision rules, utility matrix, and all parameters for other files to use e.g.
for future use.
*/
/*consider breaking decision rule solver and the simulation into separate programs */
/*Should first run the beginning program and the end program as broken into two files to make sure it works ..*/
/*some nomenclature rules:
    variables beginning with "C" or "I" refer to consumption or investment, respectively 
    variables beginning with "S" or "A" or "PI" refer to durable stock or assets or permanent income status, respectively.
    Note pi=3.14 is declare'd already.
    variables with Shk refer to income shocks of some sort.
    variables ending with "M" simply mean matrix
    variables ending with "R" refer to rate
    Underscore indicates that what follows the underscore can be thought of as a subscript
*/

/*Timing:
The time state variable goes from 1 to periods.  A sim makes periods-1 decisions.
A1, S1 are initial assets/stock; i.e., At,St are the assets/stock _before_ the t-th decisions
are made.
[this is curreently being modified.   changing the time state to be same format as other state vars, i.e.
using Tstates instead of assuming 1 to periods.  Periods will correspond to numTstates.
This is useful since if we want to switch to using a yearly model, we don't have to change 
all the parameters, we just change Tstates.  Tstates right now must be sequential integers.  The
next step will be to allow it to be any grid, like Astates etc, requiring that utility is summed over
previous decisions, similarly for income] 
*/

/* Global variables such as maxAssets are relatively unreliable. It is uniformly better to just use
Astates[rows(Astates)] instead of maxAssets.  for instance: 
if an increment is a decimal and maxAssets is
divided by the increment in calculating Astates, then depending on the way the division goes and on
the approximation of the decimal, Astates[rows(Astates)] (the effective maximum asset level) may be
slightly different than maxAssets, and comparisons to determine boundaries may fail.
*/

/*  Guessing:
 DP uses last periods optimal solution as a guess, and searches through +/- "guess" % of the arrays. set guess=1 to compare to non-guessing solution.
 Will look +- guess% * prevbestIndex.  for example, set guess=1 guarantees you look through whole space.
 Setting guess >= .5 then if prevbestIndex was right in the middle, you will still look through the whole space,
but if it's at one end, you will only look through half the space.  guess<.5 you won't look thru whole space.
 if this is screwing results up too much, you may want to add more intial periods that search the whole space.
 currently the first and last two do this.  
*/

/*
The Consumption floor (previously "Cfloor" var) that is guaranteed by the govt is the first/smallest value 
of the Cdec grid.
*/

/*
Differences between minwageDP and minwageDP_2 can be found by searching _1 ( or _2, resp.):
 newResults_tmp becomes newResults_tmp2 
"minwageDP.gau" becomes "minwageDP_2.gau"
 "graphs" becomes "graphs_2" in sim_graph();
*/

new; 
cls;


